JOHANNESBURG - The Democratic Alliance (DA) said on Saturday that it would continue to stand up to Public Protector Busisiwe Mkhwebane. This follows Mkhwebane's decision to sue DA members Glynnis Breytenbach and Werner Horn for defamation. READ: EFF regrets backing Mkhwebane for public protector She said the DA members claimed in September last year, that she was a State Security Agency spy. READ: Mkhwebane dancing to Zuma's tune: DA This was before Mkhwebane was appointed as Public Protector. Mkhwebane says the claims are false and defamatory. READ: Mkhwebane is preferred candidate to become SA's next Public Protector In a statement, the DA said it would "not shy away from this (attempting to institute a formal inquiry into her fitness for office) or any further legal action, to ensure that the Public Protector’s office is above politicking and not subject to the political interference that seems to have characterised her tenure." eNCA